				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_flag_water",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "The default properties for a soft body particle."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_flag_zombie",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "A zombie particle is one that will be destroyed after a single step with all others flagged in this way."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_flag_wall",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "This defines the particle as static, essentially creating it as an immovable object in the physics simulation, as they will remain in a fixed position no matter what collides with them. You should use this flag rather than set the density to 0."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_flag_spring",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "Spring particles produce the effect of being attached to one another, as if by a spring. Particles created with this flag are \"connected\" in pairs, with each particle being connected to the one that was closest to it at the time of creation. Once paired, particles do not change \"partners\", and the farther an external force pulls them from one another, the greater the power with which they will collide when that external force is removed."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_flag_elastic",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "Elastic particles deform and may also bounce when they collide with other rigid bodies in the physics simulation."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_flag_viscous",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "A viscous particle is one that exhibits \"clinginess\" or \"stickiness\", like oil. Viscous particles will clump and stick together more."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_flag_powder",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "Powder particles produce a scattering effect such as you might see with sand or dust."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_flag_tensile",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "Tensile particles are used to produce the effect of surface tension, or the taut curvature on the surface of a body of liquid. They might be used, for example, to create the surface tension you would see on a drop of water. Once the tension is broken, the particles bounce as if they were elastic, but also continue to attract each other. As a result, particles tend to form clusters as they bounce."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_flag_colourmixing",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"_Locale": "GB",
					"__text": "Colour-mixing particles take on some of the colour of other particles with which they collide. Note that if only one of the two colliding particles is a colour-mixing one, the other particle retains its pre-collision colour."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_data_flag_typeflags",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleDataFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "The flags value for the particle."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_data_flag_position",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleDataFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "The x and y position of the particle."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_data_flag_velocity",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleDataFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "The horizontal and vertical speed."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_data_flag_colour",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleDataFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"_Locale": "GB",
					"__text": "The colour and alpha value (hexadecimal)."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_data_flag_category",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleDataFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "The particle category (as defined when you created the particle or group to which it belongs)."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_group_flag_solid",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleGroupFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "A solid particle group prevents other fixtures from lodging inside of it. Should anything penetrate it, the solid particle group pushes the offending fixture back out to its surface, making a a solid particle group possess an especially strong repulsive force."
				},
				{
					"_Name": "phy_particle_group_flag_rigid",
					"_Class": "PhysicsParticleGroupFlag",
					"_Type": "Real",
					"_Deprecated": "false",
					"__text": "Rigid particle groups are ones whose shape does not change, even when they collide with other fixtures."
				},
